The problem arises from your inheritance hierarchy, which is fundamentally broken. It is not safe to call an overridable method from a constructor. See https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2529612/is-there-any-way-to-initialize-member-variables-of-a-subclass-in-java-before-the for more details. This is an item in Joshua Bloch&#39;s *Effective Java* (which every serious Java programmer needs to read and be familiar with).

In your `Page` class you have:

```
public abstract class Page extends AnchorPane {

    private ApplicationWindow applicationWindow;
    private NetworkManager networkManager;

    protected Controller controller;
    protected String CSS = getClass().getResource(&quot;/mspm/pages/DashboardCSS.css&quot;).toString();

    public Page(ApplicationWindow applicationWindow, NetworkManager networkManager, String CSS){

        // ...

        createView();
    }
    public abstract void createView();
}
```

where the constructor calls the overridable method `createView()`.

In the subclass `AssetDetailsView` you do the following:

```
public class AssetDetailsView extends Page {
    private LineChart&lt;String, Number&gt; temperatureChart = new LineChart&lt;&gt;(new CategoryAxis(), new NumberAxis());

    private XYChart.Series series = new XYChart.Series();

    public AssetDetailsView(ApplicationWindow applicationWindow, NetworkManager networkManager) {
        super(applicationWindow, networkManager, &quot;/mspm/pages/DashboardCSS.css&quot;);
        this.controller = new AssetDetailsController(applicationWindow);
    }



    @Override
    public void createView() {

        // ...

        series = new XYChart.Series();

        // ...
        temperatureChart = new LineChart&lt;&gt;(new CategoryAxis(), new NumberAxis());

        // ...

        series.setName(&quot;No of schools in an year&quot;);

        // ...

        temperatureChart.getData().add(series);
    }

    public void edit(){
        System.out.println(&quot;Edit: &quot; + series);
    }


}
```

If we rewrite this in equivalent form, with the inline initialization being performed in the constructor, the issue is clearer:

```
public class AssetDetailsView extends Page {
    private LineChart&lt;String, Number&gt; temperatureChart ;

    private XYChart.Series&lt;String, Number&gt; ;

    public AssetDetailsView(ApplicationWindow applicationWindow, NetworkManager networkManager) {
        super(applicationWindow, networkManager, &quot;/mspm/pages/DashboardCSS.css&quot;);
        this.temperatureChart = new new LineChart&lt;&gt;(new CategoryAxis(), new NumberAxis());
        this.series = new Series&lt;&gt;();
        this.controller = new AssetDetailsController(applicationWindow);
    }

    // ...

    @Override
    public void createView() {

        // ...

        series = new XYChart.Series();

        // ...
        temperatureChart = new LineChart&lt;&gt;(new CategoryAxis(), new NumberAxis());

        // ...

        series.setName(&quot;No of schools in an year&quot;);

        // ...

        temperatureChart.getData().add(series);
    }

    public void edit(){
        System.out.println(&quot;Edit: &quot; + series);
    }


}
```

The superclass constructor is invoked first, by necessity. That constructor calls `createView()`, which sets the values of `temperatureChart` and `series`, and sets those objects as child nodes of the object. The remainder of the subclass initialization then continues, which redefines the values of `temperatureChart` and `series` to be references to new objects (not the ones added to the scene graph). Subsequent calls to `getSeries()`, for example, return the new series (not the one used in the chart that is actually displayed, or has its name set).

Here is a simplified version of the same structure. The superclass invokes an abstract, overridable method `initializeX()` whose purpose is to initialize the variable `x` returned by the `getX()` method.

The subclass overrides `initializeX()` to initialize `x` to its &quot;correct&quot; value of 54. However, the inline intialization completes later, setting `x` to the incorrect value of 42.

```
public abstract class Super {
    public Super() {
        initializeX();
    }

    public abstract void initializeX() ;
    public abstract int getX();

    public static class Sub extends Super {
        private int x = 42 ;

        @Override
        public void initializeX() {
            x = 6 * 9 ;
        }

        @Override
        public int getX() {
            return x;
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Super sub = new Sub();
        System.out.println(&quot;What do you get if you multiple 6 by 9? &quot;+sub.getX());
    }
}
```

I&#39;m sure this is not the answer you want to hear, but here goes:

The real issue here is that your application is over-engineered. In particular, it relies far too much on inheritance. I recommend reading *Effective Java* and redesigning this in a more robust way. There is no need to subclass `AnchorPane` simply for the purpose of defining reusable functionality. There is no need to use inheritance to control creation of objects; use some kind of creational pattern (abstract factory, for example) instead. 

If you need an immediate hack, simply removing the inline initialization of `temperatureChart` and `series` might fix the immediate issue; however the design problems will inevitably lead to more issues arising at a later stage. In my opinion, it will be better to start over now than invest more on a broken design and have to do more rewriting later.

